Cookie consent banners are the primary interfaces through which users make decisions about online data collection and behavioral advertising. This study examines how consent environment factors, particularly website familiarity and cookie banner consistency, influence cookie consent decisions, while considering the roles of cognitive load, privacy concerns, and privacy fatigue. Using a realistic experimental web-based environment, the findings show that interface consistency is a strong determinant of cookie acceptance, increasing acceptance rates beyond the effects of individual privacy-related factors. The study further demonstrates that familiarity becomes influential under cognitive load, while privacy concerns’ protective effects are weakened by privacy fatigue. These findings suggest that the privacy paradox is shaped not only by individual attitudes but also by the design and cognitive conditions of consent environments, highlighting the importance of privacy-by-design approaches for meaningful user control.
